The data were completed as a component of the Geologic Resources Evaluation (GRE) program, a National Park Service (NPS) Inventory and Monitoring (I&M) funded program that is administered by the NPS Geologic Resources Division (GRD).  All GIS and ancillary tables were produced as per the NPS GIS-Geology Coverage/Shapefile Data Model (available at: http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/inventory/geology/GeologyGISDataModel.htm).  The GIS data is available as coverage and table export (.E00) files, and as a shapefile (.SHP) and DBASEIV (.DBF) table files.  The GIS data projection is NAD83, UTM Zone 13N.  That data is within the area of interest of Rocky Mountain National Park.</abstract>       <purpose>The data intended to assist NPS personnel in the protection and management of Rocky Mountain National Park.</purpose>       <supplinf>The data layers (feature classes) that comprise the Digital Geologic Map of Rocky Mountain National Park and Vicinity, Coloradoinclude: ROMOGLG (geologic units and contacts), ROMOGPT (geologic point units), ROMOFLD (geologic folds), ROMOFLT (geologic faults), ROMOATD (attitude observation points), ROMODKE (linear dikes), ROMOSEC (geologic cross section lines), ROMOMET (metamorphic grade boundaries) and ROMOMOR (glacial moraine crests).  There are three additional ancillary map components, the Geologic Unit Information (ROMOGLG1) Table, the Source Map Information (ROMOMAP) Table and the Map Help File (ROMOGLG.HLP).  Refer to the NPS GIS-Geology Coverage/Shapefile Data (available at: http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/inventory/geology/GeologyGISDataModel.htm) for detailed data layer and table specifications including attribute field parameters, definitions and domains.</supplinf>     </descript>     <timeperd>       <timeinfo>         <sngdate>           <caldate>20060202</caldate>         </sngdate> <attraccr>Attribution was primarily derived from attribution assigned to the source AUTOCAD v. 14 drawing file (.DWG; ROMO-UTM.DWG).  Attribution was re-checked by visual comparison of data with a copy of the source map (USGS I-1973) after conversion to the NPS GRE Geology-GIS Coverage/Shapefile Data Model.  Users of this data are advised to FULLY and CAREFULLY READ the "DISTRIBUTION LIABILITY" section of this metadata before using the data.</attraccr>     </attracc>     <logic>GIS data in coverage and table export (.E00) file and shapefile (.SHP) and DBASEIV (.DBF) table file formats.</logic>     <complete>All data is considered complete to the extent of the source map(s).</complete>     <posacc>       <horizpa>         <horizpar>Data, primarily derived from AUTOCAD v. 14 drawing file (.DWG; ROMO-UTM.DWG), is assumed to meet National Map Accuracy standards (William Braddock, personal communication).  A few 'WATER' contacts were checked using georeferenced USGS 7.5 minute topographic map DRGs (Digital Raster Graphics).  The PRECISION of Export (.E00) files and Shapefile (.SHP) files is DOUBLE.</horizpar>         <qhorizpa>           <horizpav>12.2</horizpav>           <horizpae>Coordinate tics on the georeferenced (registered and rectified) source map image(s) were checked against control points that had the exact specified coordinates of the tic.  The direct distance between the image tic and its control point were measured.  All measured distances were less than 50% of the required distance to meet National Map Accuracy Standards (1/50th of an inch for maps at 1:20,000 scale and smaller).</horizpae>         </qhorizpa>       </horizpa>     </posacc>     <lineage>       <srcinfo>         <srccite>           <citeinfo>             <origin>Braddock, William, A. and Cole, James C.</origin>             <pubdate>1990</pubdate>             <title>Geologic Map of Rocky Mountain National Park and Vicinity, Colorado</title>             <edition>1st</edition>             <geoform>map</geoform>             <serinfo>               <sername>Miscellaneous Investigations Series</sername>               <issue>I-1973</issue>             </serinfo>             <pubinfo>               <pubplace>Reston, Virginia</pubplace>               <publish>USGS</publish>             </pubinfo>             <othercit>Braddock, William, A. and Cole, James C., 1990, Geologic Map of Rocky Mountain National Park and Vicinity, Colorado, USGS, I-1973, 1:50,000 scale</othercit>           </citeinfo>         </srccite>         <srcscale>50000</srcscale>         <typesrc>paper</typesrc>         <srctime>           <timeinfo>             <sngdate>               <caldate>1990</caldate>             </sngdate>           </timeinfo>           <srccurr>publication date</srccurr>         </srctime>         <srccitea>USGS I-1973</srccitea>         <srccontr>Geologic features were digitized from a scanned (.TIF format at 300dpi) and georeferenced (registered and rectified) version of the source map(s).  The georeferenced source map image(s), as well as a paper copy of the source map(s), were used to attribute features, as per the NPS GIS-Geology Coverage/Shapefile Data Model, and to check the positional and attribute accuracy of the data.  Table attribution was derived from source map(s) text and notes.</srccontr>       </srcinfo>       <srcinfo>         <srccite>           <citeinfo>             <origin>Braddock, William A.</origin>             <pubdate>Unpublished Material</pubdate>             <title>ROMO-UTM.DWG AUTOCAD v. 14 drawing file</title>             <edition>1st</edition>             <geoform>map</geoform>           </citeinfo>         </srccite>         <srcscale>50000</srcscale>         <typesrc>digital file</typesrc>         <srctime>           <timeinfo>             <sngdate>               <caldate>1990</caldate>             </sngdate>           </timeinfo>           <srccurr>ground condition</srccurr>         </srctime>         <srccitea>ROMO-UTM.DWG</srccitea>         <srccontr>Data in ROMO-UTM.DWG (AUTOCAD v. 14 drawing file) is in digital format.  The data covered all of the area mapped in the published USGS source map (USGS I-1973).  The drawing file is in NAD27, UTM Zone 13N.  The coordinates of this file are UTM meters.</srccontr>       </srcinfo>       <procstep>         <procdesc>Geologic features were captured and attributed from a .DWG (ROMO-UTM.DWG) file using the ArcView 3.X CAD Reader extension.  Existing .DWG attribution were then 'converted' to Data Model attribution.  Additional data model attribution was derived from a copy of the source map.  Features were then parsed into their respective data layers and further attributed per the NPS GIS-Geology Coverage/Shapefile Data Model.  Table attribution was derived and checked using the source map(s).  Features were exported from each data layer coverage to shapefile (.SHP) format.  Tables were exported from INFO tables to DBASEIV (.DBF) file formats.</procdesc>         <srcused>USGS I-1973 and ROMO-UTM.DWG</srcused>         <procdate>20060202</procdate>         <proccont>
